<HEADLINE>
<P>
PAINTING THE LANDSCAPE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Re: Elizabeth Becker's review of Susan Fromberg Schaeffer's "Buffalo Afternoon" 
(Book Review, June 11), Where were Richard Eder, Carolyn See or Charles 
Champlin when we needed them? What does Becker, an expert on the Vietnam War, 
know about the art of fiction writing? Has she ever read Schaeffer's previous 
works, such as "Anya," "Love," or "Madness of a Seduced Woman"? Has she ever 
written a novel? 
</P>
<P>
Becker seemed overly concerned about the author's inaccuracies regarding facts 
of the war and the author's inability to give the right answers to the problems 
the war created. As a fiction wrier, this shouldn't be Schaeffer's 
responsibility. She is an artist painting the landscape the way she sees it. 
She is allowed that freedom. Schaeffer, a fine writer, deserves better. 
</P>
<P>
IRV HONER 
</P>
<P>
STUDIO CITY 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA080689-0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 91271 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
August 6, 1989, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Book Review; Page 6; Book Review Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
405 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
FICTION IN BRIEF: THE COST OF LIVING BY CHRISTOPHER ZENOWICH (HARPER &amp; ROW: 
$17.95; 267 PP.) 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SONJA BOLLE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
What would happen if an MBA wrote a novel? As "The Cost of Living" opens, Bob 
and Irene are scouring the countryside around Ann Arbor, Mich., in a company 
car -- a Caprice Classic -- looking for an apartment. Bob has just taken a 
highly demanding job as a district inventory coordinator (DIC) with a chain of 
discount drug stores; Irene needs some months to "dull out" before beginning a 
law school stint to which she intends to devote her entire being. They settle 
on a town for the compelling reason that it is the home of Kwik Kake, a snack 
they used to eat in college to satisfy the "munchies." At this point, the 
reader is not sure how seriously to take all this. The number of K's in the 
munchy food seems to indicate a parody of consumerism . . . but it's not clear. 
Expect no definite answers from Christopher Zenowich. It cannot be said, 
however, that this is a bad novel. 
</P>
<P>
"The Cost of Living" takes us through the first months of Bob's job. We get 
details we never expect in a novel: the contents of business textbooks, for 
example, such as "Store Layout as a Function of Maslow's Hierarchy of Needs." 
Soon Bob begins to travel his district and make out reports, struggling with 
the fact that his recommendations will mean unemployment for store managers who 
underperform. As Bob discovers his genius for marketing, home office takes a 
greater interest in him, and his relationship with Irene becomes more distant. 
</P>
<P>
Bob finds it difficult to explain to Irene what happens during those long days 
on the job for the same reason that novels aren't written about jobs like this. 
When Irene presses Bob for details, he routinely answers: "Oh, you know, the 
same old stuff. It couldn't possibly interest you." The fact is that Zenowich 
manages to make descriptions of the meetings, the petty triumphs, the paper 
work well done, the consumer-tricking strategies, absolutely gripping. It 
brings up all kinds of questions about what novels should do: Why shouldn't 
fiction talk about what many of us do in the daily grind? Bob and Irene are far 
from shallow; they are intelligent young people who are coming to grips with 
the great questions of growing up. Somehow, however, "The Cost of Living" 
remains a well-executed curiosity. Just as perhaps one novel can be written 
about high-energy physics, one can be written about high-level management 
training seminars, but one wouldn't want the style to take over the genre. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Book Review; Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA080689-0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 91272 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
August 6, 1989, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Book Review; Page 6; Book Review Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
571 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
FICTION IN BRIEF: THE LINE OF THE SUN BY JUDITH ORTIZ COFER (UNIVERSITY OF 
GEORGIA PRESS: $19.95; 291 PP.) 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SONJA BOLLE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Split into two equal and utterly different halves, Judith Ortiz Cofer's novel 
concerns the break in tradition that defines the first generation of a Puerto 
Rican family in New York. The narrator of the novel, Marisol, was born in the 
family's native village, Salud, but was brought to the mainland as a baby. In 
the first half of the novel, she tells the mythic tales of the Puerto Rican 
village where her father and her wild uncle Guzman grew up together. Cofer is a 
poet -- this is her first novel -- and in her descriptions of the small town, 
her eye for detail brings alive the stifling and magical world of village life: 
the seething hostilities carried over decades, the power of wives, the privacy 
that people manage to maintain even in crowded shacks. A pious brand of 
Catholicism puts the priest nominally at the center of village life. But 
spirits are also a serious force to be contended with; cleansing and protecting 
rituals are practiced daily, and the dead are as much a part of the village as 
the living. Mama Cielo, mother of Guzman and Marisol's mother Ramona, receives 
a rocking chair as an inheritance from her mother-in-law, but "not trusting her 
motives even in death, Mama Cielo had always kept the rocker out on the porch." 
</P>
<P>
From childhood on, Guzman is called "the devil's child" because of his 
uncontrollable, wayward habits. Although his mother's favorite, he brings her 
nothing but grief. At 15, he flouts all of Salud's conventions by running off 
to live with La Cabra, a village outcast who is consulted in secret for love 
potions but is openly scorned as the lost woman of the village. Guzman and his 
best friend, Rafael, make plans to escape the village. For poor Puerto Ricans 
who have never traveled beyond the nearby market town, the other place in the 
world is Nueva York, "la tierra de nieve" -- the land of snow. 
</P>
<P>
In the telling of these stories, Marisol is all but absent, surfacing only 
occasionally in the identification of characters as "my uncle" or "my father's 
family." The second half of the novel consists of Marisol's life in El 
Building, a tenement in New Jersey where Rafael has brought his wife and baby. 
Rafael is in the Navy and determined to become Americanized. On his rare visits 
to his family, he speaks only English to his children and rarely reminisces 
about his childhood. Marisol's knowledge of Puerto Rico comes mainly through 
tales told by her mother of her wild brother Guzman, who has not been heard 
from in years but continues to be the main topic in letters from Mama Cielo 
back in Salud. When Guzman suddenly surfaces at El Building, Marisol finally 
confronts a part of her family's past. 
</P>
<P>
Cofer's narrative is a bit jerky, occasionally repeating itself, as if many 
sketches had been strung together. But many of the passages are beautiful, 
particularly the scenes where Guzman wanders Salud at night, taking leave of 
the village he plans to abandon forever. The lasting impression from Cofer's 
novel is the gulf that separates poverty-stricken life on the island and the 
trapped, tenement life on the Mainland. Although all the immigrants say they 
will return to Puerto Rico one day, funerals are the only thing that draw them 
back. For the rest, their desire to return to the village only with all the 
outward signs of success -- a big car, lots of money -- keep them as 
inextricably bound to the life of El Building as they were in the native 
village. 
</P>
</TEXT>
