<HEADLINE>
<P>
OFFSHORE DRILLING AND OIL TANKERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Your editorial ("More Preventable Spills," June 27) on oil spills rightly 
emphasized prevention as the first line of defense against spills. However, you 
incorrectly suggested that oil companies are neglecting preventive measures in 
favor of spill containment. 
</P>
<P>
To the contrary, we view prevention as critical in reducing pollution from 
tankers. The industry's new $250 million oil spill program places a heavy 
emphasis on avoiding tanker accidents through recommended changes in our own 
tanker operations and in government activities regarding tankers. 
</P>
<P>
Our proposals include a preventive step that you recommend: mandatory 
participation in the Coast Guard advisory vessel traffic systems and the 
possible expansion of these systems into ports and harbors that need them. We 
also are calling for study of alternative tanker designs such as double 
bottoms, double sides and smaller tanks for vessels by an independent body such 
as the National Academy of Sciences. We are proposing other preventive measures 
including requiring maneuvering assistance from tugboats where extraordinary 
navigation hazards exist, stricter pilot standards, better training for tanker 
personnel and drug and alcohol testing. 
</P>
<P>
The industry also is creating a new spill response organization for U.S. waters 
-- designed particularly for major spills but on call for any spill -- and it 
will fund $30 million to $35 million worth of research in prevention and 
cleanup over the next five years. 
</P>
<P>
V. KENNETH LEONARD 
</P>
<P>
Transportation Director 
</P>
<P>
American Petroleum Institute 
</P>
<P>
Washington, D.C. 
</P>
</TEXT>
