<HEADLINE>
<P>
REVIVING SOME LOVING MEMORIES OF PARENTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
This is to thank Dave Larsen for the timeless article about grown-ups' sorrow 
on the loss of their parents ("The Sorrow of a Grown-Up Goodby," July 30). 
</P>
<P>
My father passed away when I was 3 and my mother in 1974, just one year after I 
had graduated from USC Engineering School. Yet, just a few days ago I had a 
wonderful dream that my mother was helping me get through college. 
</P>
<P>
I'm sure I would not have gone through engineering school without my mother's 
moral support, especially since I was the only female in my class. 
</P>
<P>
Every time I do a good job or complete a big or difficult project, I dream my 
mother is still alive; sometimes I dream about my father also. 
</P>
<P>
Who would want to forget such wonderful parents? 
</P>
<P>
EREMITA MIRANDA 
</P>
<P>
La Canada Flintridge 
</P>
</TEXT>
