<HEADLINE>
<P>
SCHOOLS WIN FEDERAL GRANT FOR MAGNET AEROSPACE PROGRAM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By TED JOHNSON, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Long Beach Unified School District has received a $3.1-million federal 
grant to create a magnet program in aerospace technology at seven city schools. 
</P>
<P>
The programs, which will be developed over the next year to start in the fall 
of 1990, will give about 2,500 students in grades four to 12 aerospace-oriented 
instruction in the physical sciences, engineering and computers. 
</P>
<P>
"The idea is that the U.S. ability to compete depends upon highly skilled 
students," Richard Van Der Laan, a district spokesman, said. "This is preparing 
for the future. It's very much in the national interest, and it's very much in 
the interest of students." 
</P>
<P>
Math and science curricula for students in the fourth through eighth grades 
will emphasize flight and space. High school students will have more vocational 
and specialized instruction. 
</P>
<P>
"We will have youngsters who will have a reason to do well in math and 
science," Van Der Laan said. 
</P>
<P>
Grant money will be used to train about 80 teachers, to upgrade science labs 
and to buy new computers and software, Van Der Laan said. 
</P>
<P>
The new magnet will be the largest of Long Beach's 36 magnet programs that are 
designed to improve education and racial balance in the schools, Van Der Laan 
said. This will be the first math and science-oriented magnet offered at 
several schools at once. 
</P>
<P>
Many of the district's magnet programs are based at just one school. Students 
will enter the aerospace program in elementary school so that they will have a 
stronger math and science background by the time they get to more specialized 
learning in high school. 
</P>
<P>
"You're building preparation into the success of high school students," Van Der 
Laan said. "They will develop a strong foundation at an early stage." 
</P>
<P>
The new program will be modeled after the Center for Aviation Technology, which 
was started last year at Lakewood High School, he said. A laboratory at 
Lakewood will be upgraded to include new computers, robotics and desk-top 
publishing. Students will be able to do realistic, computer-simulated 
experiments. 
</P>
<P>
"In a way, it is like the Wright brothers," Van Der Laan said. "We've already 
gotten off the ground, but now we are headed for outer space." 
</P>
<P>
In addition to Lakewood, the program will include Buffum, Cleveland and Monroe 
elementary schools, Bancroft Junior High School and DeMille Middle School. A 
new elementary school, which does not yet have a name, is being built in Signal 
Hill and will be part of the program when it opens in September, 1990. 
</P>
<P>
Of 180 school districts that applied for the grants, 53 received money, said 
David Eisner, a spokesman for U.S. Rep. Dana Rohrabacher (R-Lomita). The United 
States Department of Education and the Office of Civil Rights' Magnet Schools 
Assistance Program targeted $118 million for magnet schools nationwide, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
The National Aeronautics and Space Administration, the Jet Propulsion 
Laboratory, McDonnell Douglas, the Northrop Corp. and Rockwell International 
Corp. will help guide the program and train teachers, Van Der Laan said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA080689-0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 91551 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
August 6, 1989, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Westside; Part 9; Page 1; Column 1 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
2219 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
GROWING; 
</P>
<P>
THEIR OWN; 
</P>
<P>
WESTSIDERS PLANT, HOE AND WEED IN COMMUNITY GARDENS; IN RETURN THEY REAP FRESH 
PRODUCE, FLOWERS AND SOMETHING EVEN BETTER: PEACE AND QUIET 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BARBARA KOH, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Surrounded by a housing project, perched below a historic mansion, across a 
hillside overlooking Santa Monica Airport or on a busy street opposite a 
massage school, patches of earth burst forth with six-foot-tall corn and 
scarlet tomatoes, and the sweet smell of roses and herbs fills the air. 
</P>
<P>
They're the product and the pride of their fastidious caretakers, Westside 
residents who come to stoop over them, tug at weeds, and churn the soil with 
hoes and rakes. 
</P>
<P>
The parcels are community gardens, managed by cities and by nonprofit groups. 
For several hours a week of weeding and watering and for a low fee or no fee at 
all, they provide their gardeners fresh produce year-round, savings on grocery 
bills, and respite from the stress of living and working in a metropolis. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
'Biggest Bargain' 
</P>
<P>
"It's the biggest bargain in the world," said Herschel Burke Gilbert, president 
of Metropolitan Neighborhood Gardens and Farms Inc. (Metro Farms), a nonprofit 
group that oversees four gardens on the Westside and 11 elsewhere in Los 
Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
"I read a lot of things all week long which are kind of sad -- so I have to get 
away from it," Mickey Engle, a medical records clerk and doctor's assistant, 
said on a recent Saturday at Ocean View Farms in Mar Vista. She was wearing 
soil-stained white tennis shoes and a straw hat, and a grapefruit-size tomato 
was perched on her fence. Gardening on Saturdays and one night during the week 
"gives me therapy, away from all those sick people," she said. 
</P>
<P>
Santa Monica and Culver City operate gardens on city land, and West Hollywood 
leases a plot from a private landowner. Metro Farms and the Common Ground 
Garden Program, another nonprofit group, lease public and private land. 
</P>
<P>
In most cases, the leased land is obtained for free, but the property owners 
benefit because the lessees provide liability insurance, trash collection and 
weed control, said Rachel Surls, community outreach coordinator of Common 
Ground, a 12-year-old program of the University of California Cooperative 
Extension that starts gardens in low-income neighborhoods. It sponsors one 
garden on Crenshaw Boulevard and one in the Mar Vista Gardens housing project. 
</P>
<P>
If landowners have vacant lots they plan to keep vacant for a while, "they'll 
save some money on it, and it's good community relations," Surls said. "It's 
going to turn probably from a trashy, vermin-infested lot with kids hanging out 
. . . into something beautiful and nice for the community." 
</P>
<P>
Among the gardens affiliated with Metro Farms are Ocean View and one in Wattles 
Gardens Park in the Hollywood Hills, below Wattles Mansion and surrounded by 
avocado trees. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
'Victory Gardens' 
</P>
<P>
Community gardens have roots going back to at least World War I, and sprang up 
again in World War II, when food was in short supply and the federal government 
urged citizens to grow their own vegetables in "victory gardens." The 
Department of Agriculture and the Office of Civilian Defense published such 
manuals as "A Victory Gardener's Handbook on Insects and Diseases." 
</P>
<P>
Communal gardens were in style in the 1970s because of the environmental 
movement and the "back-to-the-land feelings people had," Surls said. Now, she 
said, they are cropping up once more because gardening is popular and people 
fear pesticides on their produce. There are at least 50 community gardens in 
Los Angeles County, she said. 
</P>
<P>
"It's much better and healthier" knowing how your vegetables grow, said 
Rosemary Channel, 30, pointing to her frilly, bright green lettuce at the Mar 
Vista Gardens housing project. 
</P>
<P>
The plots are also in demand by apartment and condominium dwellers. Culver 
City's garden, wedged between office bungalows for the Veterans of Foreign Wars 
and the Boy Scouts, accommodates "a lot of condo owners who have lost a place 
to dig," said Carolyn Cole, Culver City's secretary of community services. 
</P>
<P>
As a result, waiting lists have sprouted up at many gardens, with 15 people and 
more -- who should expect to wait anywhere from a few months to more than a 
year, officials said. Santa Monica has about 50 people waiting each year for 
the $18-a-year, 18-by-20-foot plots on Main Street and on Park Drive near 
Broadway, said Ramona Cicciarelli, who supervises the gardens. The wait can be 
as much as three to four years, she said. 
</P>
<P>
Some gardens, such as those in West Hollywood and at Mar Vista Gardens, charge 
the gardeners nothing, but most collect an annual fee of around $20 to cover 
trash collection, water, insurance and tools. 
</P>
<P>
The gardens come with their own sets of rules, such as limits on fences and 
pesticides, requirements on upkeep, and prohibitions on selling produce. 
</P>
<P>
At West Hollywood's triangular garden at San Vicente Boulevard and Norwich 
Drive, pumpkins and marijuana are forbidden, said garden manager Kamish Blume. 
"Pumpkins, because the city considers them an attractive nuisance -- kids jump 
over the fence and try to steal them. And marijuana, because it's illegal," she 
explained. 
</P>
<P>
Many of the green thumbs say they didn't start that way. "The first year up 
here was hysterical," recalled Barbara Schoenwetter, who has tilled at Ocean 
View since the seven-acre hillside at Centinela and Rose avenues opened 12 
years ago. "Everyone had a book -- 'How to Plant Vegetables.' " 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
'Accomplished Something' 
</P>
<P>
Carolyn Craig, who lives in the Mar Vista Gardens project, grew up in North 
Carolina, where her mother had a bountiful garden. But to her, "getting up in 
the hot sun in summer to pick vegetables, and then (having) to can all night 
long" was unappealing. 
</P>
<P>
But Craig, 33, watched last summer when part of the project's trampled lawn was 
dug up to make way for 10 garden beds, and on the spur of the moment, she 
signed up. Now, she is a convert: "You get the thrill of seeing the first 
cucumber or tomato come out. You feel you've accomplished something." 
</P>
<P>
The gardeners say they're learning by trial and error. "Whatever we want, we 
plant it -- and it if doesn't come up, we know it's not the season," quipped 
Craig's neighbor, Valita Robinson. 
</P>
<P>
But grapefruit-size tomatoes, zucchini as big as your arm and fragrant roses 
such as Mr. Lincolns don't just happen. "Spiritually, it's rewarding to grow, 
but it's a lot of work," said Eleanor Flannery, 37, an office worker who spends 
more than 10 hours a week at Ocean View tending her summer eggplant, tomatoes 
and carrots. The payoff, she said, is the joy of sending tomatoes to her mother 
in Philadelphia and to friends in Denver. 
</P>
<P>
Mark Channel, 33, a soft-spoken Mar Vista Gardens resident who belonged to a 
gang in high school, said that his patch of collards, beets, turnips and 
watermelon -- and his job at a supermarket -- "keep me out of trouble." 
</P>
<P>
"It's a good hobby," he said. 
</P>
<P>
The gardens have blossomed from mere tracts of dirt and mulch into social 
centers. The gardening mothers at the housing project come out of the 
concrete-and-stucco apartment blocks to sit on the wooden edges of the beds, 
chat and swap vegetables. Their children come to play with ladybugs and hose 
the cucumbers and tomatoes and one another. At Ocean View, people showcase 
their produce at monthly potlucks on the hillside. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Own Governments 
</P>
<P>
Ocean View and other gardens have developed their own governments. The 500-plot 
Ocean View has an elected board of directors, representatives for different 
sections of the hill, and a system for settling arguments about shade or 
leaning fences. Mailboxes, a bulletin board and a newsletter are needed to keep 
its gardeners informed. 
</P>
<P>
Scattered over the Westside as they are, the gardens reflect their gardeners. 
In the Crenshaw Boulevard garden managed by Common Ground are several rows of 
do ra ji, a bitter Korean root smaller than a carrot that is used in soups and 
salads. Nearby is a "black heritage" plot, in which Sherl Hopkins, Common 
Ground demonstration projects coordinator, pointed out sweet potatoes, okra, 
corn, sorghum, black-eyed peas, beets and several varieties of squash. 
</P>
<P>
At Ocean View, eggplant is popular. Quince and loquat trees, raspberries, 
several varieties of roses, dill and majestic red cannas dot other parts of the 
tract. 
</P>
<P>
Then there are those who plant neither vegetables nor flowers. At Santa 
Monica's Main Street garden, across the street from a massage school and a 
French bakery, Klaus Rinke has devoted two plots to pots of cacti of all shapes 
and sizes. Rinke, who was admiring his estimated 500 plants on a weekday 
evening recently, said he buys pastry at the bakery every morning and then 
breakfasts among his cacti, some of which tower 10 feet tall. He returns in the 
evening as the sun goes down. 
</P>
<P>
A sculptor from Germany, Rinke, 50, said he likes cacti "because they're like 
sculpture." 
</P>
<P>
The gardens reflect their locales in other ways. At Ocean View, the biggest 
problem seems to be gophers. "You can watch a tomato plant or a cabbage just 
disappear from the ground," said garden master Jerry Elliott. When they 
devoured her yellow wax beans, gardener Mickey Engle said, "I almost cried." 
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, at Mar Vista Gardens, Robinson lamented the recent murder of the 
homemade scarecrow by gang members. They lifted it from its seven-foot-tall 
stake, "beat it to death" and spray-painted gang names across its chest, she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Pilfering a Problem 
</P>
<P>
Pilfering, either by outsiders or other gardeners, is an occasional problem 
everywhere, but for all the troubles, the gardeners say the flavorful produce 
alone makes the effort worthwhile. 
</P>
<P>
Robinson, for example, was plucking mustard greens as she devised a menu: "Cook 
them with some salt pork, with salt and pepper, and onions. Let them cook down, 
make some corn bread, and you can have a barbecue!" 
</P>
<P>
As she picked, a burly youth sauntered past the project's garden, gestured to 
the foot-and-a-half-long cucumbers Carolyn Craig was holding, and said: "Excuse 
me -- you grew that here? That's good!" 
</P>
<P>
"People didn't think anything could grow -- (the garden is) by a playground, by 
the sidewalk, and people just walk up and down," Robinson said. 
</P>
<P>
Robinson has planted onions, greens, spinach, cabbage, green beans, cucumbers, 
carrots, garlic and basil. "When we have company, we show it off," she said. 
She estimated that the garden saves her household about $80 a month in 
groceries. 
</P>
<P>
And even the children have become fans of gardening. "I plant things, clean up, 
help pick up the papers," said Robinson's niece, Tiffany Beasley, 10, who added 
that watering was the most fun. She insisted that she likes spinach, lettuce 
and cucumbers, and that the taste is far superior to store-bought produce. 
</P>
<P>
Mark Channel Jr., 9, concurred, calling store vegetables "nasty." 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Haven for Souls 
</P>
<P>
Most of all, the gardens are a haven for tension-filled, smog-choked souls. At 
Ocean View, Elliott and Bob Eckert, lunching under umbrellas on a recent 
Saturday, were surrounded by roses, casaba gourds, eucalyptus- and mint-scented 
geraniums and squiggly, purplish ornamental kale in their plot at the top of 
the hill. The talk was of gophers. Cornstalks and cannas nearby waved in the 
breeze. "In the middle of a city like L.A., you've got this real wild world 
here," said Eckert, a Culver City condominium dweller and head of acquisitions 
at the UCLA library. 
</P>
<P>
"You go out in the garden and get peace and quiet," said Robinson at the Mar 
Vista housing project. "You don't get peace and quiet when you have eight kids 
in the house." 
</P>
<P>
To her, the garden is comforting, convenient and near-perfect. "If we're making 
tacos, we just go out and get tomatoes," she said. "I wish I could grow cheese 
and chickens out there." 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
COMMUNITY GARDENS 
</P>
<P>
Here are major community gardens on the Westside and where to call for more 
information. Some, such as the West Hollywood and Mar Vista gardens, charge 
nothing to gardeners, but most collect an annual fee of about $20 to cover 
trash collection, water, insurance and tools. 
</P>
<P>
LOS ANGELES 
</P>
<P>
