research and production next year rather than the $4.7 billion sought by the 
Pentagon, permits only two planes to be built next year rather than the five 
the Administration wants assembled and imposes performance standards on the 
unproven Stealth technology. But the amendment puts production on hold until 
the Administration devises and Congress accepts a scaled-back version of the 
Air Force's present plan to build 132 planes at a cost of $70 billion. 
</P>
<P>
Members voting yes supported the amendment. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
